Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces). Peel and grate the @garlic{3%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Finely chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(finely chopped) (or use a #food processor{} if you have one). Zest and halve the @lime{1/2} (zested and juiced).

In a #medium bowl{}, combine the @coconut milk{200%ml}, garlic, @curry powder mix{1%sachet}, coriander and half the lime juice. Mix together, then transfer 1 tbsp per person of the coconut mixture to another medium bowl along with the @British chicken thighs{3}.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then mix well. Set aside to marinate.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Pour the @water{300%ml}(for the rice) into a #medium saucepan{} with a #tight-fitting lid{}.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil on medium-high heat. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, lay the marinated chicken onto a #foil lined baking tray{}.

Roast on the middle shelf until brown and cooked through, ~{16-18%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once cooked, remove from the oven and set aside to rest for a couple of minutes.

While the chicken is in the oven, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #medium frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the onion to the pan and cook until softened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Add the @mustard seeds{1%sachet} and cook until they start to pop, ~{1-2%minutes}, then pour in the remaining coconut mixture, @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{100%ml}(for the sauce).

Season with pepper, then bring to the boil. Reduce the heat to medium-low and simmer, ~{10-15%minutes}.

While everything's cooking, roughly chop the @baby spinach{40%g} with some #scissors{}.

Once the sauce is cooked, stir in the spinach a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove from the heat and squeeze in the remaining lime juice. Taste and add salt and pepper if needed.

When everything's ready, cut the chicken into 2cm thick slices.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then share between your #bowls{}.

Top with the sliced chicken and spoon over the curry sauce to finish.

Enjoy!